{{indigenous rights}}
{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}
'''Treaty rights''' are certain rights that were reserved by [[indigenous peoples]] when they signed [[treaties]] with [[settler societies]] in the wake of [[European colonization]].  This applies to the rights of [[Alaska Natives]] and [[Native Americans in the United States]] and [[First Nations in Canada]], as well as to a smaller number of [[Inuit]] and [[Metis in Canada]] who have entered into treaties.

Treaty rights are not the only [[Aboriginal rights|rights claimed by indigenous peoples]].  Indigenous people claim inherent rights to [[self-determination]], which implies that they be recognized as [[rights-bearing]] groups (called "tribes", "bands", or "nations" depending on the place and time) capable of [[self-determination]] and [[cultural survival]].<ref name="AJI">AJI Report, Chapter 5</ref>  Once the state recognizes that there is another [[body corporate]] with [[legal personality]] capable of making binding agreements on behalf of its members, then negotiations can begin for mutual exchange and aid: a treaty.  The earliest of these agreements, between [[colonialism|colonial powers]] such the French, British, and the Dutch and various indigenous peoples of the [[Atlantic world|Atlantic coastal regions]] had the character of [[military alliances]], as between peers.  Later treaties, however, were generally about the [[cession of land]] from weakened Aboriginal peoples to expanding settler states.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/1100100028602/1100100028603|title=Treaty Rights|last=Branch|first=Government of Canada; Indigenous and Northern Affairs Canada; Communications|date=|website=www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>  By the [[Royal Proclamation of 1763]] [[the Crown|the British Crown (i.e. the state)]] declared that individual British subjects could not buy land from native nations; only the Crown could obtain land from native nations through treaty, which it could then redistribute to individuals.  This principle, which was adopted by both Canada and the United States upon gaining independence from Britain, became the legal impetus for all subsequent treaties in North America.

By signing treaties, indigenous peoples traded vast amounts of their land and resources in exchange for reserved areas of land ([[Indian reservation]]s [US terminology] and [[Indian reserves]] [Canadian terminology]) and things like protection (from attacks on their lands), [[Treaty 6|health care]], [[:Category:Indigenous education|education]], and [[Freedom of religion|religious freedom]], protection of hunting and fishing rights, and sometimes some monies as well. Because [[Article Six of the United States Constitution|Article Six]] of the [[United States Constitution]] declares treaties to be the supreme law of the land, treaties are just as valid today as they were the day they were signed, and treaty rights are still legally binding as well.  Likewise treaty rights were enshrined in Canada under [[section 35]] by the [[patriation|package of constitutional reforms of 1982]].

A common critique of the treaty relationship is that treaty rights are [[In-group favoritism|"special" rights]] given to indigenous people by the state because of their [[racial preference|racial status]].  Defenders of the treaty system argue however, that the government does not "give" treaty rights to anyone – native people reserved them when they signed treaties in a government-to-government relationship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arcbc.tripod.com/marshall-Rights.htm|title=What are treaty rights?|last=|first=|date=|website=arcbc.tripod.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>

Treaty rights are frequently subject to public debate, particularly hunting and fishing rights. Many Native nations have reserved rights to hunt and fish in their [[ancestral domain|accustomed places]], which are often lands that was given up at the treaty signing, or "ceded land". This leads to conflict with sports and commercial hunters and fishers, who are competing for the same [[Resource|limited resource]] in the same place.

Another common source of conflict is [[land management|management decisions about the land or rivers]] on which Native people have rights. Things like dams and logging have huge effects on fish and wildlife populations.  In Canadian law, government how have a court-mandated "[[duty to consult]]" indigenous peoples regarding the management process of these lands and rivers.  In the United States, no such mandate exists.

== Violations of treaty rights ==
{{incomplete list|date=January 2018}}
=== Spearfishing in Northern Wisconsin ===
{{Main|Wisconsin Walleye War}}
Beginning in the 1980s and extending into the early 1990s, Northern Wisconsin was rife in protests against [[Ojibwe]] spearfishing.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.glifwc.org/minwaajimo/Papers/3%20-%20Pierson%20--%20The%20Spearfishing%20Civil%20Rights%20Case%20(GLIFWC).pdf|title=The Spearfishing Civil Rights Case: Lac Du Flambeau Band v. Stop Treaty Abuse-Wisconsin|last=Pierson|first=Brian|date=2009|website=Great Lakes Indian Fish & Wildlife Commission|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mpm.edu/wirp/ICW-112.html|title=Spearfishing Treaty Controversy - Indian Country Wisconsin|website=www.mpm.edu|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref> The Voigt decision in 1983<ref name=":1" /> had reaffirmed that the treaties made in 1837 and 1842 still stood.<ref name=":0" /> These treaties gave the Ojibwe the rights to hunt, fish, and gather off-reservation, which was not subject to state regulation.<ref name=":1" /> This heralded a backlash of non-Natives, who believed the Ojibwe had been granted special rights. Spearheaded by groups like Stop Treaty Abuse (STA),<ref name=":0" /> often violent and racially discriminatory protests against spearfishing covered boat landings across northern [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=":1" /> This led to the case ''[[Lac du Flambeau Band of Lake Superior Chippewa|Lac du Flambeau Band of Lake Superior Chippewa Indians]] v. Stop Treaty Abuse-Wisconsin'', which culminated with Judge [[Barbara Brandriff Crabb|Barbara Crabb]] upholding the Voigt decision and many members, donors, and politicians distancing themselves from the STA, which many believed was racist.<ref name=":0" />

=== Whaling in Washington ===
The right to hunt North Pacific [[Gray whale|Gray Whales]] has been a contentious issue for the [[Makah]] people in Washington state.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/noaa-study-could-set-stage-for-resumption-of-tribal-whaling/|title=NOAA study could set stage for Makah whaling to resume|last=|first=|date=2015-03-06|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2017-04-26|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://environs.law.ucdavis.edu/volumes/32/2/brand.pdf|title=The Struggle to Exercise a Treaty Right: An Analysis of the Makah Tribe's Path to Whale|last=Brand|first=Emily|date=2009|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://nwtreatytribes.org/makah-tribe-continues-pursuit-of-treaty-whaling-right/|title=Makah Tribe pursues treaty right to whale|last=|first=|date=2015-05-04|work=Northwest Treaty Tribes|access-date=2017-04-26|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref> The Makah people ceded much of their traditional lands in the Treaty of Neah Bay in 1855, but retained the right to whale.<ref name=":3" /> The tribe voluntarily gave up this practice in 1915 because of decimated Grey Whale populations, but once the species was taken off the Federal [[Endangered species|Endangered Species]] List in 1993, the tribe sought to continue whaling. In 1999, they killed one whale, but faced immediate backlash from environmental groups and animal rights groups.<ref name=":3" /><ref name=":4" /> The [[International Whaling Commission]] (IWC) believed that the Makah tribe’s quota of harvesting up to five whales a year would not hurt the recovering population.<ref name=":4" /> Because of a number of new studies garnishing evidence for and against this practice, the issue has been tied up in court since 1999, with the tribe being unable to exercise the right given to them in the Treaty of Neah Bay.<ref name=":2" />

=== Annexation of Hawaii ===
{{Main|Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii}}
Throughout the nineteenth century, the United States made a number of treaties with the then [[Kingdom of Hawaii]], the final being in 1887. These treaties recognized the Kingdom of Hawaii as being sovereign and independent. In 1893, [[John L. Stevens]], US minister assigned to the Kingdom of Hawaii, led a group of non-indigenous people to overthrow [[Queen Lili‘uokalani]], which was backed by United States naval forces. They established a Provisional government, which then declared itself the Republic of Hawaii. In 1899, the US annexed Hawaii. Many Hawaiian sovereignty activists feel that because of the aforementioned treaties, Hawaii should today be its own Nation instead of part of the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.hawaii.edu/sites/www.law.hawaii.edu/files/content/Faculty/NHRts-HSBJ806.pdf|title=An Introduction to the Rights of the Native Hawaiian People|last=Van Dyke|first=Jon|last2=MacKensie|first2=Melody|date=July 2006|website=University of Hawaii at Mānoa|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref>

=== Dakota Access Pipeline ===
{{Main|Dakota Access Pipeline|Dakota Access Pipeline protests}}
The Indigenous people of [[Standing Rock Indian Reservation|Standing Rock reservation]] in North and South Dakota believe that the [[Dakota Access Pipeline]], which runs near their main source of water, could contaminate that source of water should it leak. The also cite the Fort Laramie Treaties of [[Treaty of Fort Laramie (1851)|1851]] and [[Treaty of Fort Laramie (1868)|1868]], which promised the land that DAPL runs through to the Sioux Tribe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bismarcktribune.com/news/state-and-regional/treaty-resonates-in-dapl-discussion/article_e9bd6a47-e14e-507e-bb0a-8ee29eb30c9e.html|title=1851 Treaty Resonates in DAPL Discussion|last=Schlecht|first=Jenny|date=November 10, 2016|work=Bismarck Tribune|access-date=2017-04-26|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> Lands were seized in 1877 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ndstudies.gov/gr8/content/unit-iii-waves-development-1861-1920/lesson-4-alliances-and-conflicts/topic-2-sitting-bulls-people/section-6-after-battle-little-big-horn|title=Section 6: After the Battle of the Little Big Horn {{!}} North Dakota Studies|website=ndstudies.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-27}}</ref>(8) and 1887 with the [[Dawes Act|Dawes Allotment Act]] that broke up reservations<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ourdocuments.gov/doc.php?flash=false&doc=50|title=Our Documents - Dawes Act (1887)|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ourdocuments.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> (9). Some call for these treaties to be reinstated and enforced today, which would put the course of the DAPT straight through Sioux lands.

